# Code Style

## General Principles

- Prefer **editing existing patterns** over inventing new ones.
- Point to canonical examples instead of creating abstractions from scratch.
- Keep functions small and single-purpose; extract helpers to `src/utils/`.
- Avoid deeply nested logic — prefer early returns and guard clauses.

## Naming

| Concept | Convention | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Files | kebab-case | `user-service.ts` |
| Classes | PascalCase | `UserService` |
| Functions / vars | camelCase | `getUserById` |
| Constants | SCREAMING_SNAKE | `MAX_RETRIES` |
| Types / interfaces | PascalCase | `UserPayload` |

## Imports

- Use ES modules (`import / export`) — never CommonJS `require`.
- Destructure named exports: `import { foo } from 'bar'`.
- Group imports: external libs → internal modules → relative paths.

## Error Handling

```typescript
// ❌ Swallowing errors
try {
  await riskyOp();
} catch (e) {}

// ✅ Log, wrap, and re-throw with context
try {
  await riskyOp();
} catch (e) {
  logger.error('riskyOp failed', { error: e });
  throw new AppError('Operation failed', { cause: e });
}
```

## Canonical Examples

> Replace these with real paths from your project:

- Component pattern: `src/components/Button.tsx`
- Service pattern: `src/services/user-service.ts`
- API route pattern: `src/api/users/route.ts`
- Test pattern: `src/__tests__/user-service.test.ts`
